title: Investigation of activation cross sections of deuteron induced reactions on indium up to 40 MeV for production of a 113Sn/113mIn generator

x4freetext: Investigation of activation cross sections of deuteron
induced reactions on indium up to 40 MeV for production
of a 113Sn/113mIn generator

x4freetext: AVF-930 cyclotron
CGR-560 cyclotron
Indium metal foils (commercial).
The 50 micron thick In foils were deposited onto
50 or 135 micron Al backing and wrapped with
6 or 12 micron Al for protection.
Three stacks were bombarded with deuterons.
Beam energies: 40 MeV (2JPNTOH) and 21 MeV (2BLGVUB),
irradiation times: 0.5 h and 1.6 h,
beam intensities: 80 nA and 25 nA.
The stacks were mounted in a Faraday-cup like target
holder equipped with a suppressor of secondary
electrons.
The activities of the produced radionuclides were
measured nondestructively, without physical separation
of target and covering foils and without chemical
separation.
The source-detector distance was kept large enough to
minimize dead time and pile-up effects and possible
influence of the non point-like geometry of the
samples compared to calibration standards.
The measurements were started shortly (0.4 h) after
end of bombardment at (2BLGVUB) and repeated three or
four times over a time period of several weeks.
At (2JPNTOH), due to the high radiation dose, before
dismantling the stacks, a cooling time of at least 4 h
was needed.

x4freetext: The energy degradation as a function of depth in the
stack was calculated from the input energy and target
thicknesses.
Al and Ti foils.
In case of the 40 MeV irradiation, the Al backing
foils served for determination of the beam intensity
and energy; in case of the 21 MeV irradiations
12 micron thick Ti foils, additionally inserted after
each Al-covered In target, were used as beam energy
and intensity monitors.
Chapter 4
Decay data were taken from NuDat2.5 database.
The monitoring method allows estimating the
uncertainty on the primary beam energy (+-0.3 MeV)
which is continuously rising in each foil through the
stack and attains +-2.1 MeV in the last foil of the
longest stack due to possible cumulative variations
on target thickness and energy degradation.
The following experimental uncertainties
were considered:
number of target nuclei including non-uniformity (3%),
incident particle flux (7%),
peak area including statistical errors (3-20%),
detector efficiency (7%) and
gamma-ray abundance and branching rate data (3%).
Typical total uncertainty is around 11%.
Possible additional uncertainties due to non-linear
effects (like half-life and waiting time) were not
accounted for.
Stack1 (2JPNTOH)
Stack2 (2BLGVUB)
Stack3 (2BLGVUB)
The experimental results were compared to the
curves calculated with the ALICE-D and EMPIRE-D
theoretical model codes and to the curves given in the
EAF-2007 and TENDL-2009 databases.
Integral yields were calculated from the
fitted experimental cross sections.
